Experience with the routine use of erythromycin for chlamydial infections in pregnancy. In an effort to prevent perinatal acquisition of Chlamydia trachomatis, we offered treatment with erythromycin ethylsuccinate (400 mg four times a day for seven days, given at 36 weeks' gestation) to 184 pregnant women with cervical chlamydial infections. Thirty-two women refused treatment 24 of their infants were followed and served as the controls. Therapy was discontinued by 5 of 10 women who had gastrointestinal disturbances. Forty-seven women who completed therapy refused infant follow-up